---
---

<section id="projects" class="py-24 px-4 sm:px-6 border-t border-border">
  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
    <p class="font-mono text-accent text-sm mb-3 tracking-widest uppercase">Projects</p>
    <h2 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold text-text-primary mb-4">
      What I've built.
    </h2>
    <p class="text-text-muted text-base sm:text-lg mb-12 max-w-2xl">
      Each project follows the same structure: what was broken, what I decided, how it was
      built, and what changed because of it.
    </p>

    <div class="flex flex-col gap-6">

      <!-- ─── Project 1: Fillory AI ─── -->
      <details class="group bg-surface border border-border rounded-xl overflow-hidden card-hover">
        <summary
          class="cursor-pointer p-6 flex items-start justify-between gap-4"
          aria-label="Expand AI Behavioral Governance Framework case study"
        >
          <div class="flex-1 min-w-0">
            <div class="font-mono text-xs text-accent mb-2 tracking-wide">Fillory AI · 2025–2026</div>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 leading-snug">
              AI Behavioral Governance Framework
            </h3>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
              Built the systems that keep multi-step AI workflows from silently degrading.
              Evaluation pipelines, context isolation, structured handoff protocols, and the
              Portland Protocol — a phase-gated event coordination system.
            </p>
            <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2 mt-4">
              {['TypeScript', 'Next.js', 'Claude API', 'Python', 'CI/CD'].map((t) => (
                <span class="font-mono text-xs px-2.5 py-1 rounded-md bg-bg border border-border text-text-muted">{t}</span>
              ))}
            </div>
          </div>
          <svg
            xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
            width="20"
            height="20"
            viewBox="0 0 24 24"
            fill="none"
            stroke="currentColor"
            stroke-width="2"
            stroke-linecap="round"
            stroke-linejoin="round"
            class="shrink-0 text-text-muted transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-180 mt-1"
            aria-hidden="true"
          >
            <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"></polyline>
          </svg>
        </summary>

        <div class="px-6 pb-8 border-t border-border pt-6 space-y-8">

          <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
            <div>
              <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold text-accent mb-2 uppercase tracking-wide font-mono">Problem</h4>
              <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
                AI-powered applications degrade in predictable ways: outputs drift from
                defined constraints over a workflow, models optimize for user approval over
                accuracy, and multi-step pipelines have no built-in verification between
                stages. There were no off-the-shelf tools for enforcing workflow-level
                behavioral constraints at the application layer.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold text-accent mb-2 uppercase tracking-wide font-mono">Approach</h4>
              <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
                Rather than relying on model-level behavior alone, the solution was to build
                constraint and evaluation systems at the orchestration layer — validation
                logic that defines acceptable output boundaries, testing infrastructure that
                verifies workflow consistency, and structured handoff protocols that reduce
                contamination between pipeline stages.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Architecture diagram -->
          <div>
            <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold text-accent mb-4 uppercase tracking-wide font-mono">Architecture</h4>
            <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row items-stretch sm:items-center gap-2 font-mono text-xs">
              <div class="flex-1 bg-bg border border-accent/40 rounded-lg p-4 text-center">
                <div class="text-accent text-xs mb-2 font-semibold tracking-widest uppercase">Layer 1</div>
                <div class="font-bold text-text-primary mb-1">Infrastructure</div>
                <div class="text-text-muted text-xs leading-relaxed">Multi-machine production · Cloud code sandbox · GitHub CI/CD</div>
              </div>
              <div class="text-accent font-bold text-lg text-center sm:text-left" aria-hidden="true">→</div>
              <div class="flex-1 bg-bg border border-accent/40 rounded-lg p-4 text-center">
                <div class="text-accent text-xs mb-2 font-semibold tracking-widest uppercase">Layer 2</div>
                <div class="font-bold text-text-primary mb-1">Portland Protocol</div>
                <div class="text-text-muted text-xs leading-relaxed">Phase gates · Versioned events · Retryable webhooks</div>
              </div>
              <div class="text-accent font-bold text-lg text-center sm:text-left" aria-hidden="true">→</div>
              <div class="flex-1 bg-bg border border-accent/40 rounded-lg p-4 text-center">
                <div class="text-accent text-xs mb-2 font-semibold tracking-widest uppercase">Layer 3</div>
                <div class="font-bold text-text-primary mb-1">Agent Runtime</div>
                <div class="text-text-muted text-xs leading-relaxed">Semantic normalization · Task state tracking · Regression detection</div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Engineering constraints -->
          <div>
            <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold text-accent mb-4 uppercase tracking-wide font-mono">Engineering Constraints</h4>
            <div class="space-y-4">
              <div class="border-l-2 border-accent-warm pl-4">
                <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-text-primary mb-1">Trust as Permission to Slip</p>
                <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
                  The planner tracked a user–agent trust score that was intended to relax
                  behavioral constraints as trust increased. The logic is inverted. A trusting
                  user is not a forgiving user — they're a <em>dependent</em> one. The more
                  they trust the agent, the less they scrutinize its outputs. High trust is
                  precisely when the agent must be most reliable, not least. The system had
                  built a permission structure where earning trust was a license to degrade.
                </p>
                <p class="text-xs text-text-muted mt-2 italic">
                  Diagnosed by coming to the codebase fresh and running structured
                  agent-assisted interrogation of the system's assumptions.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="border-l-2 border-accent-warm pl-4">
                <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-text-primary mb-1">17-Service Production Recovery</p>
                <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
                  Led live production recovery of a 17-service AI platform following a
                  hardware failure — implementing process persistence and boot automation to
                  achieve zero-downtime intervention with no data or service loss.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="border-l-2 border-accent-warm pl-4">
                <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-text-primary mb-1">Agents Optimizing Against Their Own Guardrails</p>
                <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
                  A recurring pattern: when presented with a problem, early agents would
                  identify the fastest path to resolution — which often meant recommending
                  deletion of the <code class="font-mono text-xs bg-bg px-1 py-0.5 rounded">CODEBASE_RULES</code> files.
                  These were the behavioral governance constraints that defined the project:
                  its design principles, architectural boundaries, behavioral contracts. The
                  agent wasn't malfunctioning. It was doing exactly what it was built to do.
                  "Quickly" and "correctly" were not the same objective.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold text-accent mb-2 uppercase tracking-wide font-mono">Result</h4>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
              Delivered AI-powered applications with improved workflow reliability and reduced
              output inconsistency. Created a structured developer environment adopted for
              government compliance projects, where deterministic, verifiable behavior was a
              hard requirement.
            </p>
          </div>

          <!-- Efficiency Guide artifact -->
          <div class="bg-bg border border-accent/30 rounded-xl p-5">
            <div class="font-mono text-xs text-accent mb-2 tracking-wide uppercase">Documented Artifact</div>
            <p class="text-sm text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-3">
              <strong class="text-text-primary">AI Developer Efficiency Guide</strong> — a
              detailed operational protocol covering context topology, bounded memory systems,
              deterministic handoffs, session restart protocols, and sub-agent coordination
              patterns. Written during production development, not after.
            </p>
            <a
              href="/efficiency-guide.md"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
              class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 text-sm font-semibold text-accent hover:text-accent/80 transition-colors"
            >
              Read the Efficiency Guide
              <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M18 13v6a2 2 0 0 1-2 2H5a2 2 0 0 1-2-2V8a2 2 0 0 1 2-2h6"/><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"/><line x1="10" y1="14" x2="21" y2="3"/></svg>
            </a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- ─── Project 2: Office Ally ─── -->
      <details class="group bg-surface border border-border rounded-xl overflow-hidden card-hover">
        <summary
          class="cursor-pointer p-6 flex items-start justify-between gap-4"
          aria-label="Expand Angular Platform Reliability & Security case study"
        >
          <div class="flex-1 min-w-0">
            <div class="font-mono text-xs text-accent mb-2 tracking-wide">Office Ally · 2022–2024</div>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 leading-snug">
              Angular Platform Reliability & Security
            </h3>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
              Owned code review for an offshore team, rebuilt the signup flow, and
              introduced OWASP-aligned security practices across a production healthcare
              software platform.
            </p>
            <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2 mt-4">
              {['Angular', 'C#', '.NET', 'SQL', 'OWASP', 'Octopus Deploy'].map((t) => (
                <span class="font-mono text-xs px-2.5 py-1 rounded-md bg-bg border border-border text-text-muted">{t}</span>
              ))}
            </div>
          </div>
          <svg
            xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
            width="20"
            height="20"
            viewBox="0 0 24 24"
            fill="none"
            stroke="currentColor"
            stroke-width="2"
            stroke-linecap="round"
            stroke-linejoin="round"
            class="shrink-0 text-text-muted transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-180 mt-1"
            aria-hidden="true"
          >
            <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"></polyline>
          </svg>
        </summary>

        <div class="px-6 pb-8 border-t border-border pt-6 space-y-6">
          <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
            <div>
              <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold text-accent mb-2 uppercase tracking-wide font-mono">Problem</h4>
              <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
                A healthcare software platform's front-end was being developed by an offshore
                team with inconsistent code quality and security practices. The signup process
                was also losing potential customers due to friction and bugs in the flow.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold text-accent mb-2 uppercase tracking-wide font-mono">Approach</h4>
              <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
                Established a formal code review process for the offshore team, became
                Angular-certified to give technical authority to the reviews, and prioritized
                the signup flow rebuild as the highest-impact improvement. Implemented
                OWASP-aligned security practices across the platform.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold text-accent mb-2 uppercase tracking-wide font-mono">Architecture</h4>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
              .NET API endpoints for business logic, Angular frontend with clean component
              separation, ReCaptcha integration for bot prevention, Octopus for
              environment-specific deployment configuration, and field-level encryption for
              sensitive data at system boundaries.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold text-accent mb-2 uppercase tracking-wide font-mono">Result</h4>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
              Improved platform reliability and scalability. Signup process rebuild directly
              contributed to new customer acquisition. Offshore team output quality measurably
              improved with formal review cadence and clear standards.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- ─── Project 3: Prosper IT — Nav Menu ─── -->
      <details class="group bg-surface border border-border rounded-xl overflow-hidden card-hover">
        <summary
          class="cursor-pointer p-6 flex items-start justify-between gap-4"
          aria-label="Expand Course Navigation Menu case study"
        >
          <div class="flex-1 min-w-0">
            <div class="font-mono text-xs text-accent mb-2 tracking-wide">Prosper IT · 2020–2021</div>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 leading-snug">
              Course Navigation Menu
            </h3>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
              The code I'm most proud of. Rebuilt the course nav from a featureless progress
              bar into a full nested accordion with position tracking — then spent two weeks
              fixing the 7-second runtime it caused.
            </p>
            <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2 mt-4">
              {['C#', '.NET MVC', 'Razor', 'OutputCache', 'JavaScript', 'SQL'].map((t) => (
                <span class="font-mono text-xs px-2.5 py-1 rounded-md bg-bg border border-border text-text-muted">{t}</span>
              ))}
            </div>
          </div>
          <svg
            xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
            width="20"
            height="20"
            viewBox="0 0 24 24"
            fill="none"
            stroke="currentColor"
            stroke-width="2"
            stroke-linecap="round"
            stroke-linejoin="round"
            class="shrink-0 text-text-muted transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-180 mt-1"
            aria-hidden="true"
          >
            <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"></polyline>
          </svg>
        </summary>

        <div class="px-6 pb-8 border-t border-border pt-6 space-y-6">
          <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
            <div>
              <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold text-accent mb-2 uppercase tracking-wide font-mono">Problem</h4>
              <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
                The course nav was a clickable progress bar with no labels — students had to
                guess what percentage corresponded to what page. The new nested accordion
                idea worked logically but took 7 seconds to load per page, making it
                unusable. The runtime cost came from running nested DB queries for every
                page load.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold text-accent mb-2 uppercase tracking-wide font-mono">Approach</h4>
              <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
                Two-layer caching strategy: server-side <code class="font-mono text-xs bg-bg px-1 py-0.5 rounded">OutputCache</code> (keyed by
                courseId + modified date) for the menu structure itself, and client-side
                cookies for user-specific position data. The expensive query only runs when
                course content changes.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold text-accent mb-2 uppercase tracking-wide font-mono">Architecture</h4>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
              Nested C# ViewModels (Course → Section → Subsection → Page), server-side
              Razor partial view, <code class="font-mono text-xs bg-bg px-1 py-0.5 rounded">OutputCache</code> attribute on the
              rendering method with <code class="font-mono text-xs bg-bg px-1 py-0.5 rounded">VaryByParam</code> on courseId and modified date.
              JavaScript injects user position on load from a client-side cookie, places an
              arrow on the current page, and disables links beyond the student's progress.
            </p>
          </div>

          <!-- Before/after runtime callout -->
          <div class="grid grid-cols-2 gap-4">
            <div class="bg-bg border border-border rounded-xl p-4 text-center">
              <div class="font-mono text-2xl font-bold text-accent-warm mb-1">~7s</div>
              <div class="text-xs text-text-muted">Before caching</div>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-bg border border-accent/30 rounded-xl p-4 text-center">
              <div class="font-mono text-2xl font-bold text-accent mb-1">1.39s</div>
              <div class="text-xs text-text-muted">After caching</div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Screenshots -->
          <div class="space-y-4">
            <img
              src="/images/NavMenu_FullPage_Open.PNG"
              alt="Completed course nav menu showing nested accordion with current position marker"
              class="w-full rounded-lg border border-border"
              loading="lazy"
            />
            <div class="grid grid-cols-2 gap-4">
              <img
                src="/images/NavMenu_RuntTime_Bad.PNG"
                alt="Browser dev tools showing ~7 second page load before caching"
                class="w-full rounded-lg border border-border"
                loading="lazy"
              />
              <img
                src="/images/NavMenu_RuntTime_Good.PNG"
                alt="Browser dev tools showing 1.39 second page load after caching"
                class="w-full rounded-lg border border-border"
                loading="lazy"
              />
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- ─── Project 4: Prosper IT — Progress Bars ─── -->
      <details class="group bg-surface border border-border rounded-xl overflow-hidden card-hover">
        <summary
          class="cursor-pointer p-6 flex items-start justify-between gap-4"
          aria-label="Expand Dual Progress Bars case study"
        >
          <div class="flex-1 min-w-0">
            <div class="font-mono text-xs text-accent mb-2 tracking-wide">Prosper IT · 2020–2021</div>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 leading-snug">
              Dual Progress Bars
            </h3>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
              The old progress bar silently gave every student wrong information — it didn't
              account for mandatory live project weeks. Built a new system that handles
              variable-length bootcamps, weighted course completion, and user-configurable
              display preferences.
            </p>
            <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2 mt-4">
              {['C#', '.NET MVC', 'JavaScript', 'jQuery', 'SQL'].map((t) => (
                <span class="font-mono text-xs px-2.5 py-1 rounded-md bg-bg border border-border text-text-muted">{t}</span>
              ))}
            </div>
          </div>
          <svg
            xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
            width="20"
            height="20"
            viewBox="0 0 24 24"
            fill="none"
            stroke="currentColor"
            stroke-width="2"
            stroke-linecap="round"
            stroke-linejoin="round"
            class="shrink-0 text-text-muted transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-180 mt-1"
            aria-hidden="true"
          >
            <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"></polyline>
          </svg>
        </summary>

        <div class="px-6 pb-8 border-t border-border pt-6 space-y-6">
          <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
            <div>
              <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold text-accent mb-2 uppercase tracking-wide font-mono">Problem</h4>
              <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
                The progress bar only reflected actual course material, leaving 2–4 weeks of
                mandatory live project time unaccounted for. Students were systematically told
                they were further behind than they actually were — and the discrepancy varied
                by bootcamp length (10–16 weeks) and course page count vs. actual completion
                time.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold text-accent mb-2 uppercase tracking-wide font-mono">Approach</h4>
              <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
                Created a <code class="font-mono text-xs bg-bg px-1 py-0.5 rounded">LMSCourseOrder</code> join table to link courses to bootcamps,
                allowing a single live project course to be reused across multiple camps.
                Weighted each course by time-to-complete rather than page count. Offloaded
                the ahead/behind calculation to JavaScript running on the client.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold text-accent mb-2 uppercase tracking-wide font-mono">Result</h4>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
              Accurate progress reporting for all bootcamp lengths. Students who complained
              about the stress of behind-schedule warnings got per-component display toggles
              — each bar element could be shown or hidden independently and the preference
              persisted.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="grid grid-cols-2 gap-4">
            <img
              src="/images/ProgressBar_Full_Ahead.png"
              alt="Progress bar showing student is ahead of schedule"
              class="w-full rounded-lg border border-border"
              loading="lazy"
            />
            <img
              src="/images/ProgressBar_Full_Behind.png"
              alt="Progress bar showing student is behind schedule"
              class="w-full rounded-lg border border-border"
              loading="lazy"
            />
          </div>
        </div>
      </details>

    </div>
  </div>
</section>
